diff:1166712618:1166712618:=1,50d0%0a%3c !Platform specific issues%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Windows%0a%3c On Windows you need to install MinGW and MSYS since this is the only environment supported by the open source version of Qt on this platform.%0a%3c %0a%3c On Windows you'll have to use CMakeSetup instead of ccmake to view and edit CMake build parameters; when you run CMakeSetup for the first time you'll be prompted with a dialog asking to select the type of the makefile to generate; select MSYS.%0a%3c %0a%3c You can download MinGW/MSYS from this website: http://www.mingw.org%0a%3c %0a%3c Make sure you also install the latest vesion of binutils, if not you might get an error at link time (@@ld.exe:...assertion fail...@@), while building some libraries (e.g. coin). ''Binutils 2.17.50 update - 2006-08-29'' seems to work.%0a%3c %0a%3c OpenBabel cannot be built out of the box with MinGW, it is therefore required that you build it from source code following the instructions in openbabel_mingw.txt or that you download a prebuilt OpenBabel 2.x MinGW library from Molekel's website.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Linux%0a%3c %0a%3c The described build process has been tested only on SuSE 10.x, and Fedora Core 5.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Mac OS X%0a%3c %0a%3c Not tested with universal binaries. There should be no issue in building universal binaries, provided you build/get all the required libraries first.%0a%3c %0a%3c On Mac some libraries and tools can be installed with ''darwinports'' or fink.%0a%3c Check on the [[http://darwinports.opendarwin.org | Darwinports]] and [[Fink | http://fink.sourceforge.net]] websites for information on the available packages.%0a%3c %0a%3c if you use darwinports to install OpenBabel it will be automatically installed under @@/opt/local@@ and the include directory to set in the cmake variable will be%0a%3c @@/usr/local/include/openbabel-2.0@@ (or some other version number).%0a%3c %0a%3c If you install a pre-built version of Coin3D make sure you also install the tools package which is required to build applications outside Xcode.%0a%3c %0a%3c When building VTK make sure that @@VTK_USE_CARBON@@ is ON.%0a%3c %0a%3c OpenMOIV doesn't build out of the box on Mac OS; if you have OpenGL installed as a framework (and want to use it as a framework)%0a%3c then you cannot use @@#include %3cGL/gl.h>@@ in the source code because there is no @@GL@@ directory in the OpenGL.framework/Headers directory.%0a%3c To build OpenMOIV you can use the include files in the @@/usr/X11R6/include/GL@@ directory, note that these include files are usually different from the ones in the @@OpenGL.framework/Headers@@ directory.%0a%3c To have CMake use the files in the X11 dir open OpenMOIV's CMakeLists.txt and%0a%3c add the following line before @@INCLUDE_DIRECTORIES(${OPENGL_INCLUDE_PATH})@@:%0a%3c *@@SET( ${OPENGL_INCLUDE_PATH} /usr/X11R6/include )@@%0a%3c %0a%3c Build with @@cmake -Dcoin:int=1@@ then @@make@@%0a%3c %0a%3c You will then have to copy the @@include/ChemKit2@@ directory into your preferred include dir (e.g. @@/usr/local/include@@) and the @@libChemKit2@@%0a%3c lib into your preferred lib dir (e.g. @@/usr/local/lib@@).%0a%3c %0a%3c Due to the fact that some libraries used by Molekel do have include files that @@#include %3cGL/gl.h>@@ you also need to configure CMake to use @@/usr/X11R6/include as the value of @@OPENGL_INCLUDE_DIR@@; this is an advanced options and therefore you need to press @@'t'@@ to have it displayed.%0a%3c %0a%3c If you want to use the @@OpenGL.framework@@ @@#includes@@ you might as well copy the @@OpenGL.frameworks/Headers@@ files to a @@GL@@ directory and change%0a%3c the value of @@OPENGL_INCLUDE_DIR@@ to the directory containing the @@GL@@ directory; there are however other issues if you do this: if some code references @@GL/glx.h@@ compilation will fail because there is no @@glx.h@@ file in the @@OpenGL.framework/Headers@@ directory.%0a%3c %0a%3c @@IV_INCLUDE_DIR@@ and @@IV_LINK_DIR@@ do not have to be set on Mac if you install the 